  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions involves several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Techniques used by criminals to disguise illegally obtained funds\n\n2. Initial Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States was first comprehensive legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention addressed money laundering related to drug trafficking\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Expansion:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Increased reporting requirements and enforcement mechanisms\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n\n5. Global Regulatory Framework:\n- Increasing international coordination\n- Comprehensive regulatory systems in most developed countries\n- Ongoing refinement of detection and prevention strategies\n\n6. Recent Trends:\n- Growing focus on cryptocurrency and digital financial transactions\n- Enhanced technological monitoring\n- Stricter international enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legal framework continues to evolve in response to changing financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
